# Alpine linux - iperf3 as a service

**iperf3 as a service** inside an **Alpine Linux LXC container** using OpenRC (Alpine’s init system).

This assumes:

*   You’re inside an **Alpine LXC**
*   You have **iperf3 installed**
*   You want it to run automatically at boot as a daemon/service

***

# ✅ Step 1 — Install iperf3

```sh
apk add iperf3
```

***

# ✅ Step 2 — Create an OpenRC service file

Create a new service script:

```sh
nano /etc/init.d/iperf3
```

Paste the following:

```sh
#!/sbin/openrc-run

name="iperf3"
command="/usr/bin/iperf3"
command_args="-s"  # run server
pidfile="/run/iperf3.pid"
command_background="yes"

depend() {
    need net
    after firewall
}
```

### What this does:

*   Runs **iperf3 in server mode (`-s`)**
*   Starts it **in the background**
*   Ensures networking is up first

***

# ✅ Step 3 — Make the service executable

```sh
chmod +x /etc/init.d/iperf3
```

***

# ✅ Step 4 — Add it to the default runlevel (start at boot)

```sh
rc-update add iperf3 default
```

***

# ✅ Step 5 — Start the service now

```sh
rc-service iperf3 start
```

***

# 🎉 Verify it’s running

Check service status:

```sh
rc-service iperf3 status
```

Check process:

```sh
ps aux | grep iperf3
```

Test from another machine:

```sh
iperf3 -c <LXC_IP>
```

***

# Optional: Run on a specific port

Edit:

```sh
command_args="-s -p 5202"
```

***

# Optional: Run as a “reverse mode preferred” test server

```sh
command_args="-s --forceflush"
```

***

# If you want it to log output

Add inside the service file:

```sh
output_log="/var/log/iperf3.log"
error_log="/var/log/iperf3.err"
```

